bib_record.title: Neutron yields from thick Be targets bombarded with deuterons or protons

free_txt: The deuteron and proton beams
were produced by an energy-variable compact
cyclotron with a fast internal beam-pulsing system.
The TOF spectra had to be corrected for the
satellite structure of the pulsed beam. The spectra
obtained with the two highest recoil proton energy
thresholds were used to scan the time structure of
the beam and to determine the intensity of each
satellite pulse relative to the main pulse; hence
the corrected TOF spectra were obtained by
iteratively subtracting the individual contributions
of every satellite pulse.
In tables data are given in 10**12 x yield/Coulomb/sr
compiler converted them in yield/microCoulomb/sr
An NE213 liquid scintillator in a cylindrical
aluminum container 5.08 cm in thickness and diameter,
coupled to a fast multiplier served as a photon and
neutron detector.
The quadratic summation of all contributions
results in a total uncertainty of 4.5% for neutron
energies above 5 MeV, 6% at E-n = 1 MeV and 10.5 %
at E-n = 400 keV. It includes:
* statistical uncertainties
* uncertainty in the determination of the beam
charge on the Be target
* uncertainty due to the detector efficiency;
* uncertainty for the corrections due to the
satellite structure of the beam
* uncertainty of the correction fuction due to air
attenuation
The deuteron and proton beams
were produced by an energy-variable compact
cyclotron with a fast internal beam-pulsing system.
The experiments were performed with the
time-off-flight (TOF) spectrometer at the PTBs
accelerator facility.

diameter of 35 mm, was directly flanged to the beam
pipe sealed by a Viton O-ring. The target disc was
